=========================================================
CLASSES AND OBJECTS IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Class:
A user-defined data type (blueprint/template) that defines properties
(data members) and behaviors (member functions).

Object:
An instance of a class. Memory is allocated only when an object is
created.

=========================================================
REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE
=========================================================

Class      : Car Blueprint
Object     : Actual Car

Class defines:
• Color
• Speed
• Brand

Objects:

Car c1;
Car c2;
Car c3;

Each object has its own copy of data members.

=========================================================
CLASS SYNTAX
=========================================================

class Employee
{
private:
    int id;
    string name;

public:
    void display()
    {
        cout << id;
    }
};

=========================================================
OBJECT CREATION
=========================================================

Employee e1;      // Object
Employee e2;      // Object

Memory is allocated for:

id
name

Functions are NOT stored inside every object.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Employee
{
public:
    int id;

    void display()
    {
        cout << id << endl;
    }
};

int main()
{
    Employee e1;

    e1.id = 100;

    e1.display();
}

Output:
100

=========================================================
MEMORY REPRESENTATION
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    int x;
    int y;

    void show()
    {
    }
};

Object:

------------------
x
------------------
y
------------------

Member functions are stored only once in Code/Text Segment.

Every object contains only data members.

=========================================================
CLASS vs OBJECT
=========================================================

Feature            Class                 Object
--------------------------------------------------------
Meaning            Blueprint             Instance
Memory             No                    Yes
Creation           Compile Time          Runtime
Existence          Logical Entity        Physical Entity
Contains           Data + Functions      Actual Data

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Car
{
public:
    int speed;
};

Car c1;
Car c2;

Memory:

c1.speed
c2.speed

Each object gets its own copy of non-static data members.

=========================================================
HOW ARE MEMBER FUNCTIONS CALLED?
=========================================================

Compiler internally converts:

obj.show();

into:

show(&obj);

A hidden pointer called:

this

is passed.

=========================================================
THIS POINTER
=========================================================

class Test
{
    int x;

public:
    void setX(int x)
    {
        this->x = x;
    }
};

Compiler internally:

void setX(Test* this, int x)
{
    this->x = x;
}

=========================================================
ACCESSING MEMBERS
=========================================================

Object Operator:

obj.member

Pointer Operator:

ptr->member

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

Employee e;
e.display();

Employee* p = &e;
p->display();

=========================================================
SIZE OF EMPTY CLASS
=========================================================

class Test
{
};

cout << sizeof(Test);

Output:

1

=========================================================
WHY SIZE IS 1?
=========================================================

Every object must have a unique address.

Compiler allocates 1 byte to ensure unique addresses.

=========================================================
SIZE OF CLASS
=========================================================

class Test
{
    int x;
    char c;
};

Size depends on:
• Data members
• Padding
• Alignment
• vptr (if virtual functions exist)

Functions do NOT contribute to object size.

=========================================================
CLASS WITH VIRTUAL FUNCTION
=========================================================

class Base
{
public:
    virtual void fun()
    {
    }
};

Contains:

vptr

Object size increases by pointer size.

64-bit system:

sizeof(Base) >= 8 bytes.

=========================================================
STATIC DATA MEMBERS
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    static int count;
};

Static members are NOT part of object size.

Reason:
Only one shared copy exists.

=========================================================
CONSTRUCTOR INVOCATION
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    Test()
    {
        cout << "Constructor";
    }
};

Test t;

Output:

Constructor

Constructor is called automatically when object is created.

=========================================================
DESTRUCTOR INVOCATION
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    ~Test()
    {
        cout << "Destructor";
    }
};

Destructor is called automatically when object goes out of scope.

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is a Class?

Answer:
A user-defined data type that acts as a blueprint for creating objects.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. What is an Object?

Answer:
An instance of a class with its own memory for non-static data members.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. When is memory allocated?

Answer:
When an object is created, not when the class is defined.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Are member functions stored in every object?

Answer:
No.

Functions are stored once in the code segment and shared by all objects.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. What is stored inside an object?

Answer:
• Non-static data members
• vptr (if virtual functions exist)

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Why is sizeof(empty class) = 1?

Answer:
To ensure every object has a unique address.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Do static data members contribute to object size?

Answer:
No.

Only one shared copy exists outside the object.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. Do member functions contribute to object size?

Answer:
No.

Functions are stored separately in memory.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. What contributes to class size?

Answer:
• Data members
• Padding and alignment
• vptr (if virtual functions exist)

---------------------------------------------------------

Q10. What is the hidden parameter passed to member functions?

Answer:
this pointer.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

A class is a user-defined blueprint that encapsulates data members and
member functions, while an object is an instance of that class. Memory
is allocated only when objects are created. Objects contain non-static
data members and possibly a vptr, while member functions are stored only
once and shared among all objects.

